Restaurant Order and Billing Management System
1. Introduction
Organization
Considering a small restaurant that sells food items like burgers, pizzas, pasta, and beverages. To manage the orders and keep track of the food items and drinks they serve and generate correct bills, they’ll need a system. 
Problem
The traditional method of taking orders can be slow and time-consuming and can also make some mistakes. Calculating bills manually may result in incorrect totals(bills) and keep customers waiting. This is a headache for restaurants. So, the restaurant needs a computer software program to make these tasks easier.
Purpose
The purpose of this project is to create a Restaurant Order and Billing Management System using Python. This system helps restaurant staff to manage their food items on the menu, take customer orders accurately, and generate bills quickly. This system will speed up the order taking process and reduce mistakes in generating bills. 
Scope
The system will do the following things:
•	Display the food items that are available on the menu.
•	Help find the specific food items on the menu.
•	Add items to customer orders. 
•	Remove items from customer orders.
•	Calculate the total cost of the order.
•	Generate bills for the customers quickly.
•	Apply tax and discount to the customer bills when necessary.

2. System Design
The system consists of five main classes.
Classes and their Responsibilities
MenuItem
This part represents a single menu item.
Attributes:
•	item_id 
•	name 
•	price 
Methods:
•	display_item()
•	update_price ()
•	get_price()
•	apply_discount() 
Menu
Manage all the items available on the menu.
Methods:
•	add_item() 
•	remove_item() 
•	search_item() 
•	display_menu() 
Order
Takes and stores customer orders.
Methods:
•	add_item() 
•	remove_item()t 
•	view_order() 
•	calculate_total() 
Bill
Generates the total customer bills.
Methods:
•	calculate_tax() 
•	apply_discount() 
•	calculate_final_amount () 
•	print_bill() 
Restaurant
This part acts like the overall controller of the system.
Methods:
•	load_menu() 
•	show_menu() 
•	take_order() 
•	generate_customer_bill() 
Class Relationships
The Restaurant class is the main controller of the system, and it helps other classes work together.
The Menu class manages all the food and drinks that are available on the menu of that restaurant. It keeps track of all the MenuItem objects and each MenuItem is a thing on the menu with a specific Id, name and price.
The Order class takes and manages customer orders. When a customer places an order, the MenuItem which they select are added to their ‘order’  and the Order class keeps track of the items selected for the order and generates the bill for it.
The Bill class generates the final bill for the customer based on their order. For the bill to be generated the information is taken from the Order class and then the total cost is calculated. Additional taxes or discounts are applied to the bill when necessary and the final bill is generated that the customer must pay.
The Restaurant class works together with the Menu, Order, and Bill classes. Whereas the Menu and Order classes are dependent on the MenuItem.
The Bill class depends on the Order class to get order details and generate bill.
Relationship Summary
•	The Restaurant class controls the overall system. 
•	The Menu class contains multiple MenuItem objects. 
•	The Order class contains selected MenuItem objects ordered by the customer. 
•	The Bill class uses information from the Order class to generate the final bill. 
•	All classes work together to provide menu management, order processing, and bill generation functionalities. 

Data Management
Now, the menu items and customer orders are stored in computers memory using Python lists.
Examples:
self.items = A list to store items available on the menu.
self.order_items = A list to store the items that are ordered by the customers.

3. Implementation Overview
The project was made using Python Language.
Classes and Objects
Each component of the restaurant system is represented as a class.
For example:
item1 = MenuItem(1, "Burger", 120)
This object is used for a menu item.
Functions and Methods
To organize things methods were used in every class
For example:
def calculate_total(self):
total = 0
for item in self.order_items:
total += item.price
return total
This method gives the total cost of an order.

Conditional Statements
To handle user choices, decision making structures were used.
For example:
if choice == "1":
restaurant.show_menu()
Loops
To repeatedly display the system menu until the user chooses to exit, loops were used.
For example:
while True:
Exception and Error Handling
Input validation was implemented to prevent invalid discount percentages.
Example:
if 0 <= discount_percent <= 100:
The system also handles cases where a menu item is not found.
Example:
print("Item not found.")
Readability and Modularity
The project was divided into multiple files:
•	menu_item.py 
•	menu.py 
•	order.py 
•	bill.py 
•	restaurant.py 
•	main.py 
This design improves readability, maintainability, and code reuse.

